In the current situation, the Fed faces conditions that have not existed before and that could accelerate a recession.
Specifically, the gross domestic product will approach its historical low point for an increase in the Fed’s interest rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate increases since 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was less than 4.5%.
Even though in the second quarter of 2015 the value was 3.6%, few expect the situation to persist, with the third quarter reaching only 1.5%, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Increasing interest rates in such a fragile economy could be risky and could raise the question “if this time is different,” Deutsche said.
Market players have been preparing for a growth decision by the Fed all year round, with all eyes focused on this week’s meeting of the Federal Open Market Commission, which closes on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an increase in interest rates on the occasion of this meeting, futures trades indicate a probability of only 25%.
“In our post-1950 study, all of the interest rate growth cycles to date have been in a super-profit growth cycle, with GDP eclipsing peaks before the recession very quickly after the start of recovery,” the report said.
