On the occasion of the most anticipated meeting in recent years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran Mahogany table to decide whether it’s time to raise a key interest rate for the first time ever.
Above them, at the end of the central bank’s meeting room, will be seen a wall painting of the United States.
The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, Fed President, and his colleagues must put the economic interests of the nation above all else.
The Central Bank has received a double task from Congress: to maximize the employment rate in the U.S. and maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be the factor X in a decision too difficult to anticipate, which will be announced on Tuesday, and which will determine if the US economy is ready to be debunked by the unprecedented stimulus offered by the short-term interest rate and the near-zero-starting 2008.
Even though most data indicate a strong growing economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already precautionary about adding volatility by increasing the reference rate to federal funds – even by only a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and foremost issues they will pursue,” said Lindsey M. Pigza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to increase the rate of interest, the growing uncertainty on the world market is enough to give them arguments to wait longer,” she said.
There is no consensus on the Fed’s decision, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
Approximately half of Bloomberg’s recently questioned economists anticipated an increase in the interest rate this week.
But financial markets are expected to delay the Fed, a key indicator showing that the probability of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a fall on the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policymakers would mitigate the blow promising it would take a long time to grow.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The move was triggered by expectations that Fed decision makers would keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising for the Fed to raise interest rates right now,” Lonski said.
If the Fed’s decision makers would do so, “they should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in the financial markets.”
Other experts said an increase in the interest rate would calm financial markets because it would remove the uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be about to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step toward a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that he expected an increase in the interest rate this year despite objections raised by liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, the growth of the labour market was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Wage earnings have shown signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fail to reach the central bank’s annual target, the Fed’s decision makers said a key reason was the temporary effect of falling oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the tension in the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, global financial markets began to enter into fibrillation at the end of this month, after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 16% below the record high in May as investors feared that slowing the Chinese economy would pull down global growth.
The market declined somewhat this month, with the Dow index now at about 10% below the May peak.
For Fed decision makers, market agitation is added to the complex calculation of the moment of interest rate increase.
“Without what has happened in the financial markets and the news of the weakening Chinese economy in recent weeks, it would be more firm within the meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and the former Fed.
Now, he anticipates that they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy and they have hardly any data to rely on after the events in China,” Oliner said.
The welfare of the global economy is not one of the major interests of the Fed, so it should practically not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been enormous.
Ben S. Bernanke’s simple hint in 2013 that the Fed might “anger” its monetary expansion triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials are expected to not only monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
Its decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at the wellness management firm Investnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, VA, said this month that “the Fed has a history of oversized reaction to changes in the financial market that seem to have nothing to do with economic bases.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported the increase in interest rates, offered as an example the 1998-99 decisions.
A financial crisis that affected Asia caused the Fed to cut the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, “despite the implications with limited identification potential for U.S. development,” Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reverted to those declines.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England interest rate committee.
The last turbulent period does not rise far to that level, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to be in a position to be afraid of an increase in interest rates because markets have become angry,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds a double mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in this regard, I do not think it should take action prematurely.
